Subject: [PATCH] Synthesized: unintercalate uses endBy instead of splitOn
 (after 82edf4e8af6b20f43567e7448ce106470d3ec015)

Historical context: commit 82edf4e fixed `unintercalate = endBy` to
`unintercalate = sepBy`. The buggy form drops a trailing empty chunk
when the input ends in the delimiter, breaking the inverse property
`intercalate x (unintercalate x s) == s`. On modern HEAD the binding
reads `unintercalate = splitOn` (`splitOn` is the modern name for
`sepBy`; `sepBy = splitOn` in the same module). Reverting to the
historical `endBy` form reproduces the bug.

The `+++` side is modern HEAD (fixed); the `---` side is the
historical buggy formulation. `git apply -R` installs the bug.
---
 src/Data/List/Split/Internals.hs | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/src/Data/List/Split/Internals.hs b/src/Data/List/Split/Internals.hs
--- a/src/Data/List/Split/Internals.hs
+++ b/src/Data/List/Split/Internals.hs
@@ -529,7 +529,7 @@ endByOneOf = split . dropFinalBlank . dropDelims . oneOf

 {-# DEPRECATED unintercalate "Use splitOn." #-}
 unintercalate :: (Eq a) => [a] -> [a] -> [[a]]
-unintercalate = endBy
+unintercalate = splitOn

 -- | Split into \"words\", with word boundaries indicated by the given
 --   predicate.  Satisfies @'Data.List.words' === wordsBy
